english:
  title: A Refutation of the Man of Hua
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the Tang dynasty, there was a man of Hua who cut flesh from his thigh to heal his mother's illness. When the commandant heard of this, he erected a memorial gate and exempted him from taxes. But Han Yu responded: "When parents fall ill, one treats them with careful preparation and medicine. I have never heard of anyone maiming their own limbs in the name of filial devotion. Is this not a grave violation of filial piety? Even if such an act conformed to filial duty, it would not warrant erecting a memorial gate. This is merely what any human being should do—why celebrate it as extraordinary?" I respectfully disagree.

    When one's parents fall ill, as their child you will exhaust a thousand remedies and ten thousand medicines seeking one cure. You will invite shamans and pray to spirits, and though you know such things are delusion, you will leave nothing undone. If a renowned physician declares that human flesh alone can make an effective medicine, will you sit idle and watch your mother die rather than comply? Or will you spare your own limbs hoping for her recovery? My limbs are the legacy my parents entrusted to me. The ancients said that returning one's body whole to the earth is filial piety. Yet if I treasure my limbs, so too will others treasure theirs. Who would willingly mutilate themselves for another's mother? Then the medicine cannot be obtained, and the illness cannot be cured.

    If Han Yu himself were thrust into such circumstances, what would he do? The gentleman does indeed cherish his body, but there are times when it cannot be cherished—these arise from circumstances beyond one's control. Thus a son dies for filial piety, a minister for loyalty. This is what Han Yu meant by "dying in the midst of rebellion." When facing rebellion, to abandon one's life is natural. But when facing grave illness that has not yet reached death's threshold, should one then cling to a mere piece of flesh? One who clings to flesh when facing danger would surely not cling to life when facing rebellion.

    Han Yu further argued: "Only after one has endured hardship while preserving loyalty and filial piety without seeking mere survival should one be honored with memorial gates and rank. This is how to encourage virtue." Yet if this were so, a son or minister would have no place to fulfill filial duty and loyalty during times of peace, and the state would gain neither loyal ministers nor filial sons except in times of crisis. Moreover, since fulfilling one's nature is the proper conduct of all people, though common folk cannot exhaust their nature while only the sage can perfect it—this act of cutting flesh is not the conduct of one perfecting their nature. Yet if we follow the logic of its flaws to their conclusion, we would make the perfecting of one's nature into something that all people should do, thereby leveling the sage with the common person. Is this not absurd?

    Alas, from ancient times to now, who lacks parents? Who is not someone's child? Yet those who truly fulfill filial duty are rare. Many love wealth and favor their wives and children while neglecting their parents' sustenance. Wealth is external; wives and children, though united with us, are distinct from our own being, yet men still favor them—how much more so one's own flesh? How many in this world know they have a body but forget they have parents? The Han emperor Liu Bang, who sent word asking for broth when his father was threatened as a hostage, and Wen Jiao, who cut his robe to depart, were both esteemed rulers and renowned ministers, yet in their darkest hour neither recalled their parents. The man of Hua, by contrast, knew only that he had a mother and not that he had a body.

    The danger lies not here, but in this: some in the world, being cruel and reckless, commit unseemly acts to gain momentary praise. This is truly culpable. But if one were to proclaim a single man filial, one would be declaring an entire district devoid of filial sons. The ancient sages did not all teach the same way; their paths diverged according to circumstance. Later generations followed their footprints and honored their achievements. All sages grounded their learning in filial piety and fraternal duty. Since humans first existed, only Emperor Shun is called supremely filial, and only Zengzi is noted for honoring his father's will. Must all other sages be deemed unfilial? If Han Yu's doctrine were to prevail, jealous men gaining power would suppress virtue, obstruct filial conduct throughout the land, and disturb the people's understanding—would not the harm be great?

    Some have said: "Han Yu was a man of letters who cherished the ancient way and crafted superior arguments. Yet he attacked the man of Hua harshly. Are you not equally harsh in attacking Han Yu? When the Great Unity dissolves, skill and clumsiness become visible. When Great Simplicity fragments, black and white are distinguished. To honor one man's filial piety in one district, one must wait until all in that district are filial. Is not this reasoning sound?"

    I have read in the New History of Tang that men used human flesh to treat wasting illnesses, and many fathers and sons cut their flesh to present it. Some were given silk, some memorial gates. Even then such practices were excessive. If we encourage this, we will mutilate all humanity. One cannot teach through the body alone; those merely fulfilling their filial duty's ordinary conduct would become unfilial. Can Han Yu have spoken without insight?

    I respond: The ancient kings established teachings for the people that were indeed unified and generous. They spoke of distinguishing the virtuous from the corrupt—they did not say that honoring one man as virtuous means declaring an entire district lacks the good. When heaven and earth separated, good and evil were divided. Since good and evil divided, difference between excess and deficiency cannot be avoided. Thus we use the Mean as our standard. But among the people, few can long practice the Way of the Mean. Hence it is said: "Observe people within their category to understand the virtuous; observe faults to perceive benevolence." Though cutting flesh is excessive, it belongs to the category of filial piety. To judge it unfilial—is this not itself excessive?

    To nourish parents in life, worry for them in illness, grieve them in death, to dare not harm even the hair and skin inherited from them, to maintain reverence throughout life—this is the straight path of the filial child. If one loses a foot, one does not go out. If one's hands are injured, one knows one is freed from blame. Some have offered their entire body to their lord or father, making it lighter than a goose feather. How much more so a portion of flesh? If alternatives exist to heal a mother without cutting flesh, there is no need to constrain oneself to do so. But if no alternative exists and only such flesh can save her, then though I incur the reproach of the Mean-following gentleman, I too would become a man of Hua.

    Those who establish teachings must aim at the Mean so their words endure, passing through all ages without corruption. When I read the "Response of the Man of Hua," I find many flaws in its reasoning. I suspect it was fabricated, not truly from Han Yu's hand. Otherwise, the man of Hua's conduct departs from the Mean, and Han Yu's response equally departs from the Mean.
